This is a preview of the UPEZ cart for a store: Dream Recovery  
[https://upez-frontend.vercel.app/api/internal-preview-cart?domain=dreamrecovery.io](https://upez-frontend.vercel.app/api/internal-preview-cart?domain=dreamrecovery.io)  
The cart is loaded from a builder.io template.  
If you open Network tab and refresh, you will see the request:  
![][image1]  
The response of this request is an object of the cart slider that is fed to Builder SDK to load to the frontend.  
And in \[templateID\]…data.settings, you will find an array, whose children are input fields. Let’s call each item here “a template’s setting”

![][image2]  
These input fields are used in the UPEZ app in each Shopify store to customize the look and feel of the cart slider.  
![][image3]  
In the builder response, you will also see “blocks”. This object describes the layers, or components and their components' children that make up the elements in the cart slider. Its structure is very similar to how React renders components.  
![][image4]  
Very often, you will see some components has binding related to one of the template’s settings like this:  
![][image5]  
**Your task is to create a hover effect:**

1. When users hover over an element that has binding related to a template’s setting, highlight that element like this:  
   ![][image6]  
2. At the same time, log the template’s setting object in the console.

Here’s an example of a final outcome:  
![][image7]  
You could write your code in your IDE and then inject it in the console to run it.
